description:
News / Infotainment creators are getting content strikes at a record rate. Channels are facing the prospect of deletion for the 'crime' of using a few seconds of copyright content. While the internet is divided over who's right and who's wrong & what is 'fair use' - very little focus is being given to the REAL cause of this mess. 
A US made law - that has little relevance for @youtubecreators in India - but massive scope of misuse. Will @YouTube act to save news content creators in India or is this the end??

🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨
Here's what YOU can do to put pressure on YouTube to update / change / modify its US made, flawed 3-strike-policy. Send a mail to support-in@google.com - tell them how this policy is being misused in India / why they need to update it for Indian law.
OR
You can also send a mail to the supremecourt@nic.in - so that they can take suo moto cognizance of the matter and pass an order that leads to a clear definition of 'fair use' 
OR 
You can write to the govt - asking them to come clean on what footage can be used what cannot be used - https://pgportal.gov.in/

Bhai, yeh sawaal ka jawab samajhne ke liye humein dono incidents—2019 aur 2025—ko dekna hoga aur yeh pata lagana hoga ki Pakistan ke counter-attack mein India ka zyada nuksaan kyun hota hai. Chalo, ek-ek karke samajhte hain.

### *2019 Ka Incident*
February 2019 mein, Pulwama terrorist attack ke baad India ne Pakistan ke Balakot mein airstrikes kiye. Iske agle din, Pakistan ne jawabi hamla kiya. Pakistan ke fighter jets ne Indian airspace mein ghuskar ek dogfight shuru ki, jisme India ka ek MiG-21 gira diya gaya aur pilot ko capture kar liya gaya. Isme India ka nuksaan zyada dikha kyunki ek jet down hua aur pilot pakda gaya, jabki Pakistan ka koi bada loss report nahi hua.

*Kyun Hua Yeh?*
- *Pakistan Ki Air Defense:* Pakistan ke paas strong air defense systems the, aur unki air force ne F-16s aur JF-17s ko effectively use kiya. India ke Mirage 2000s ko counter karne mein woh kaamyaab rahe.
- *Quick Response:* Pakistan ne turant jawab diya, jo shayad India ne expect nahi kiya tha. Yeh surprise element unke favor mein gaya.
- *Ghar Ka Fayda:* Pakistan apne airspace mein tha, jahan unka radar network aur anti-aircraft systems full active the, jabki India enemy territory se operate kar raha tha.

### *2025 Ka Incident (Hypothetical)*
Ab 2025 ki baat karen toh yeh ek imaginary scenario hai. Maan lo ki May 2025 mein India ne ek terrorist attack ke jawab mein Pakistan par punitive strikes kiye, aur chaar din tak conflict chala. Dono taraf ke nuksaan hue, lekin yeh kaha ja sakta hai ki Pakistan ne phir se effectively retaliate kiya.

*Kyun Hua Yeh?*
- *Defensive Advantage:* Jab koi country apne area mein lad rahi hoti hai, toh usko radar aur air defense ka poora support milta hai. India jab attack karta hai, toh woh Pakistan ke territory mein hota hai, jahan unka control kam hota hai.
- *Pakistan Ki Capability:* Pakistan ki air force aur military modern hai. Unke paas advanced jets (jaise F-16s, JF-17s) aur upgraded air defense systems hain, jo India ke attacks ko rok sakte hain.
- *Strategy:* Pakistan ki military strategy mein har Indian attack ka bada jawab dena shamil hai. Iska matlab woh hamesha equal ya zyada force ke saath retaliate karte hain.

### *Overall Kyun India Ka Zyada Nuksaan Hota Hai?*
1. *Defensive Position:* Pakistan jab defend kar raha hota hai, toh usko apne systems ka full fayda milta hai, jabki India attack ke waqt risk mein hota hai.
2. *Surprise Factor:* Pakistan ka retaliation unexpected aur tezi se hota hai, jaise 2019 mein next day attack.
3. *Military Strength:* Pakistan ki air force aur defense systems kaafi capable hain, jo India ke modern equipment ke bawajood unko counter kar sakte hain.
4. *Chhota Lekin Tez:* Pakistan ka size chhota hai, lekin unki strategy mein tezi aur zor se jawab dena shamil hai.

Toh bhai, yeh pattern isliye dikhta hai kyunki Pakistan apne defensive advantage aur quick response ka fayda uthata hai. 2019 mein yeh saaf dikh gaya, aur 2025 mein bhi shayad yahi hua hoga.

comments.text:
Greetings from Nepal.

Recently, Nepal witnessed a troubling attempt by those in power to suppress digital freedom. In a blatant move to preserve their political comfort, the government sought to impose sweeping restrictions on social media—platforms that have become powerful tools for truth, resistance, and accountability. Unlike traditional media, often constrained by corporate and political interests, independent creators and YouTubers speak with an unfiltered voice. That authenticity threatens those who thrive in opacity.

Under the guise of regulation, a social media bill was hastily passed in parliament, designed less to protect the public and more to control the narrative. But the people saw through the charade. Creators, citizens, and digital communities across the nation rose in unison—not with violence, but with clarity, unity, and unshakable conviction. And for now, we’ve managed to defend our space for free expression.

Now, we see a similar pattern unfolding in India. Power is once again trying to mask fear with legislation, to silence dissent by calling it disruption. But this is not the time to retreat—it’s the time to connect. Across borders, people must stand united against this new face of authoritarianism disguised in digital policies.

When rulers fear voices they cannot script, it means the truth is gaining ground. Let them be afraid.

In solidarity,
Nepal stands with all who refuse to be silenced.
